</tbody></table>";}i:4938;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:284:"<strong>Coming Soon from Too Big to Fail:</strong> The global financial crisis of 2008 showed just how connected the international financial system is, and how exotic operations taking place in big banks can affect everyone in ways that no one ever considered. Here‚Äôs what‚Äôs next.";}i:4939;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:304:"<strong>The Great Wallow:</strong> That‚Äôs what Warren Hunter, protagonist in Michael Pocalyko‚Äôs The Navigator, calls the US economy. Corporations achieve record profits, the Dow reaches new highs, but so much of the country struggles as income disparity increases. An explanation and the way forward.";}i:4940;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:319:"<strong>The Corporate Imperative:</strong> This is the age of the corporation. The basic idea of a corporation evolves at an astonishing pace with huge implications for society, individual rights, and commerce that may be unintended and unforeseen. Where American commerce is heading with or without the corporate form.";}i:4941;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:317:"<strong>Transparency and Directorship:</strong> More is demanded of corporate directors than ever before, but very few people (including some in the boardroom), really understand the roles of corporate directorship for the company and for society, including along the wide divide between public and private companies.";}i:4942;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:328:"<strong>Why Can‚Äôt We All Get Along?:</strong> Leaders in government and business approach economic challenges from wildly different perspectives.  Life experience is only part of the reason.  Incentives tell more of the story, and explain why the political-business disconnect is only going to get worse before it gets better.";}i:4943;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:324:"<strong>Navigating Gridlock:</strong> Political gridlock is now a fixture of American life.  There are few options for political relief, and a federal government with more effect on commerce‚Äîgood and bad‚Äîthan ever before. What business, financial, and not-for-profit leaders have to do in order to plan and strategize.  ";}i:4944;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:316:"<strong>Governing the Ungovernable:</strong> Largely unnoticed outside universities, a national crisis is slow-boiling.  Facing the challenge of for-profit education companies, our Academy is becoming ungovernable. Reasons why the crisis is accelerating, some challenges coming, and some solutions that are required.";}i:4945;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:309:"<strong>The New Literature of the Digital Moment:</strong> Society and technology continue to change at whipsaw speed.  Literature is caught in the moment, and the fundamental nature of ‚Äúthe humanities‚Äù is also changing. What the word literary may now mean is going to alter public expression permanently.";}i:4946;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:319:"<strong>Paths to Publishing in Publishing‚Äôs Watershed:</strong> This is book publishing‚Äôs watershed decade. Michael Pocalyko made a literary debut at the age of 22 then returned to publish a major novel 37 years later‚Äîwhile a CEO. How it all happened and what other aspiring writers can learn from his experience.";}i:4947;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:288:"<strong>The Unexpected Future of Combat Trauma:</strong> Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD) is a major theme in The Navigator, manifesting itself in unexpected ways. A deep and meaningful discussion of combat trauma and how it will affect America and society in the next three decades.";}i:4948;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:319:"<strong>The Meaning of Beirut:</strong>  On October 23, 1983, 241 US Marines serving in the Multinational Force in Lebanon were killed by a suicide bomber who drove a truck full of explosives into the Beirut barracks. Michael Pocalyko was there, airborne. Reflections on the meaning of that act today and in the future.";}i:4949;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:310:"<strong>Privacy and Conspiracy in the Age of Homeland Security:</strong> The world changed on 9/11 when we entered the age of homeland security. Lines blur between intelligence and law enforcement, conspiracy theories grow, and privacy is compromised. Finding meaning in a world turned upside down, decade two.";}i:4950;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:48:"Visit Michael Pocalyko‚Äôs website to learn more";}i:4951;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:50:"Read Michael Pocalyko‚Äôs posts at Algonquin Redux";}i:4952;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"www.macmillan.com";}i:4953;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"More Speaker Info";}i:4954;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:27:"http://michaelpocalyko.com/";}i:4955;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"926";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta