</tbody></table>";}i:4975;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:438:"<strong>The Real-Life Gangster Squad:</strong> An audio-visual presentation on the eight anonymous cops who slept with Tommy guns under their beds and traveled about town in two rusted-out Fords to battle the mob in Noir Era Los Angeles‚Äîa time and place where truth was not found in the sunlight and justice not obtained in a marble courthouse. The true story that inspired Warner Bros. to revive the gangster film genre it made famous.";}i:4976;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:830:"<strong>Gangster Mythology, Real Gangsters, and the American Gangster Film:</strong> Paul Lieberman uses his behind-the-scene experience with the making of a modern gangster film to explore the dark flipside to America‚Äôs Horatio Alger myth. The multimedia presentation explores how real gangsters and film portrayals have played off each other from the Prohibition days of Al Capone through the modern times of John Gotti, illustrated by such big screen classics as Scarface and White Heat and the modern-day mob epics, the Godfather trilogy and The Sopranos. But no single figure blurred the lines between real life and fiction more than Los Angeles‚Äô signature gangster Mickey Cohen, who spent his last years of freedom promoting his standing as a gangster to sell book and movie rights to any sucker with a dollar to spare. ";}i:4977;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:995:"<strong>Bugsy Siegel, Mickey Cohen, and the Era of the Jewish Gangster:</strong> They helped fund the insurgents fighting to create a Jewish state in the Middle East even as they forged alliances‚Äîand waged death feuds‚Äîwith the Italian mob. Benjamin (Bugsy) Siegel and Meyer Harris (Mickey) Cohen were tough street kids who became two of the most high profile hoodlums of the 20th Century and why not? They rose through the ranks of hoodlums at a time when a child of the Yiddish theater, Paul Muni, was picked by Hollywood to be the first actor to play the most feared of the Sicilians, Al Capone, on the screen. All through their rise and inevitable fall, their identity as Jews was a central element of their criminal careers built on contradictions, menace and, yes, humor. How else to explain Mickey‚Äôs big scam of offering to sell his soul to Jesus‚Äô up-and-coming voice in America, the great evangelist Billy Graham? A colorful introduction to the legends of Jewish organized crime. ";}i:4978;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:584:"<strong>The Billionaire, the Butler . . . and the S√©ance to Bring Them Back:</strong> A journey through the final chapter in the life of the 20th century‚Äôs quintessential heiress, Doris Duke, who died mysteriously in the old Rudolph Valentino mansion, an early center of psychic sessions to commune with the dead. When she left her fortune in care of her flamboyant butler, and he soon died as well, how better to get to the heart of the matter than to call on Hollywood‚Äôs leading medium. . . . Take a multi-media journey into the occult and the underside of the City of Angels. ";}i:4979;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:609:"<strong>They Ain‚Äôt No Angels‚ÄîThe Phenomenon of Hospital Killers:</strong> They top the lists of mass killers because it‚Äôs so easy to get away with murder in a hospital, where people die all the time. The public often brands them as ‚ÄúAngels of Death‚Äù but compassion for the old and sick is never their motivation. The talk traces such killers over the years‚Äîfrom the ‚ÄúArsenic and Old Lace‚Äù case on‚Äîwhile introducing the audience to perhaps the most prolific ‚ÄúAngel‚Äù of all, Efren Saldivar, who confessed to killing 60 to 100 patients while working the appropriately named Graveyard Shift.";}i:4980;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:78:"Watch Paul Lieberman tell the story of Gangster Squad on MSNBC‚Äôs Morning Joe";}i:4981;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:53:"Read a Q&A with Paul Lieberman in The Huffington Post";}i:4982;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"www.macmillan.com";}i:4983;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"More Speaker Info";}i:4984;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:66:"http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/3036789/ns/msnbc-morning_joe/#48526700";}i:4985;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:103:"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barbara-ernst-prey/gangster-squad_b_2412461.html?utm_hp_ref=entertainment";}i:4986;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:25:"http://www.macmillan.com/";}i:4987;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:44:"http://us.macmillan.com/author/paullieberman";}i:4988;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:12:"videos_video";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:4989;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"videos_description";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:4990;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:20:"biography_upload_pdf";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:4991;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"934";s:8:"meta_key";s:12:"photo_credit";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:4992;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"936";s:8:"meta_key";s:20:"_yoast_wpseo_linkdex";s:10:"meta_value";s:1:"0";}i:4993;O:8:"stdCl