</tbody></table>";}i:6009;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:334:"<strong>Lincoln Shall Die in this City</strong> Daniel Stashower relates the race-against-the-clock story of how Allan Pinkerton, America‚Äôs first private eye, detected and thwarted a plot to assassinate Abraham Lincoln in 1861, at the start of the Civil War as the President-elect traveled to Washington for his first inauguration. ";}i:6010;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:664:"<strong>I Have Earned this Right:</strong> Allan Pinkerton and the American Worker The Pinkerton Detective Agency would eventually become notorious as a band of skull-crackers and union-busters, but Stashower tracks Allan Pinkerton‚Äôs early commitment to the rights of working men and labor unions, beginning with his involvement with a radical labor movement that brought him under fire‚Äîliterally‚Äîin his native Scotland. For groups with an interest in business and organized labor, Pinkerton‚Äôs journey from youthful radical to brutal strike-breaker‚Äîoften at the behest of America‚Äôs robber barons‚Äîoffers a unique perspective on America‚Äôs Gilded Age.";}i:6011;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:976:"<strong>Kate Warne, Pink Lady: America‚Äôs First Female Private Eye Kate Warne, the 23-year-old widow who persuaded Allan Pinkerton to hire her as America‚Äôs first female private eye </strong>in 1856, is a forgotten icon of Women‚Äôs Studies. At a time when the work of Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony had barely begun, Kate Warne was already in the field, working side by side with male operatives and living the dangerous life of a Pinkerton detective.  One investigation found her posing as a fortune-teller, ‚Äúthe only living descendant of Hermes,‚Äù to lure secrets from a superstitious suspect; another saw her forging a ‚Äúuseful intimacy‚Äù with the wife of a suspected murderer. ‚ÄúA female detective‚Äù she told Pinkerton, ‚Äúmay go and worm out secrets in ways that are impossible for male detectives.‚Äù She became one of Pinkerton‚Äôs most trusted and effective operatives, and played a crucial role in getting Abraham Lincoln safely to Washington. ";}i:6012;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:839:"<strong>Free in Name; a Slave in Fact: Allan Pinkerton and the Underground Railroad</strong> By day, Allan Pinkerton was America‚Äôs top law man; by night he flouted the law‚Äîand the nation‚Äôs Fugitive Slave Act‚Äîas a station master on the legendary ‚ÄúUnderground Railroad,‚Äù helping runaway slaves make their way north to freedom. This presentation explores Pinkerton‚Äôs forgotten work as an abolitionist crusader and his close partnership with the infamous John Brown in the days leading up to Harper‚Äôs Ferry. ‚ÄúMore than one dark night,‚Äù he wrote, ‚Äúfound us working earnestly together in behalf of the fleeing bondsman who was striving for his liberty.‚Äù This exciting and little-known chapter of Pinkerton‚Äôs storied career will appeal to audiences with a special interest in the Civil War and the abolitionist movement.";}i:6013;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:882:"<strong>Who Are Those Guys? The Birth of the Pinkerton Detective Agency </strong> Stashower charts the rise of Allan Pinkerton from a barefoot immigrant to the world‚Äôs most famous detective. The story takes him from his first case, in which he outwitted a wily counterfeiter, to his nail-biting effort to save Lincoln‚Äôs life in 1861. The discussion will illustrate how Pinkerton and his men (and women) pioneered forensic and investigative techniques that are still in use today, and changed the public‚Äôs perception of what it meant to be a lawman. Pinkerton and his agents became legendary for their relentless, single-minded pursuit of criminals, and the dramatic Pinkerton logo‚Äîwith the motto ‚ÄúWe Never Sleep‚Äù coiled beneath the image of a stern, unblinking eye‚Äîbecame a potent emblem of vigilance, bringing the phrase ‚Äúprivate eye‚Äù into the American lexicon.  ";}i:6014;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:70:"Read Daniel Stashower's New York Times piece "New York's Black Dahlia"";}i:6015;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"www.macmillan.com";}i:6016;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"More Speaker Info";}i:6017;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:91:"http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/08/nyregion/thecity/08ciga.html?_r=1&ref=thecity&oref=slogin";}i:6018;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:25:"http://www.macmillan.com/";}i:6019;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"related_links_link";s:10:"meta_value";s:54:"http://us.macmillan.com/thehourofperil/DanielStashower";}i:6020;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:12:"videos_video";s:10:"meta_value";s:75:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_detailpage&v=BOSesEJlEEs#t=10s";}i:6021;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:18:"videos_description";s:10:"meta_value";s:38:"Online Interview with Daniel Stashower";}i:6022;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:20:"biography_first_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:6023;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:19:"biography_last_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:6024;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"508";s:8:"meta_key";s:20:"biography_upload_pdf";s:10:"meta_value";s:0:"";}i:6025;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s