</tbody></table>";}i:6107;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:756:"<strong>Reverse Innovation - Create Far from Home, Win Everywhere:</strong> It‚Äôs a preoccupation in many boardrooms that today‚Äôs high-growth hot spots are all in the developing economies, which will account for a jaw-dropping two-thirds of global economic growth over the next generation. But what is less well understood is what it will take to win. For decades, most global corporations have followed a simple strategy: create great products and services for home markets, and then export them. But what worked in the past is no longer good enough‚Äîthe needs and opportunities are just too different. As a result, corporations must learn the new trick of reverse innovation: learn to innovate in emerging economies, and bring those innovations home.";}i:6108;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:654:"<strong>The Other Side of Innovation:</strong> ‚ÄúGenius is one percent inspiration, ninety-nine percent perspiration.‚Äù Thomas Edison said it over a century ago. Nobody listened. When companies launch innovation initiatives, they focus almost all of their time and energy on that initial one percent‚Äîthe thrilling hunt for the breakthrough idea. They draw guidance from countless books and articles that treat innovation as though it is synonymous with creativity. It is not. The reality is that an idea is only a beginning. Innovation is not just the much-anticipated light-bulb moment. It is also a long, hard journey‚Äîfrom imagination to impact. ";}i:6109;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:640:"<strong>Leading Innovation in Healthcare Delivery:</strong> We can‚Äôt wait for policy makers on Capitol Hill to save our troubled health care system. Instead, we need a new generation of health care leaders‚Äîphysicians and executives alike‚Äîthat are ready to remake the system from the grass roots, through innovation and entrepreneurship. While health care may seem impossibly complex, the reality is that it is hard to walk more than ten yards without tripping over an idea or an innovative pilot project with tremendous potential. This presentation will show why these pilots so rarely achieve full potential, and what to do about it.";}i:6110;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:676:"<strong>The Leading Innovation Workshop:</strong> This workshop details Six Essential Principles to make innovation happen inside your organization. Workshop participants discover a straight-forward approach to executing an innovation initiative involving, in particular, a special kind of (dedicated) team and a special kind of (disciplined) plan. This workshop is not about creativity, brainstorming, searching for ideas, or even selecting the best. It is about achieving an idea‚Äôs full potential without getting eaten or run-over by the very organization that is trying to bring it to life.  It is about enabling a team in the present that can deliver you to your future.";}i:6111;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:75:"Visit Chris Trimble‚Äôs website at The Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth";}i:6112;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:96:"Read Chris Trimble‚Äôs Harvard Business Review blog post, ‚ÄúGoogle and the Myth of Free Time‚Äù";}i:6113;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:62:"Read a review of The Other Side of Innovation in The Economist";}i:6114;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"979";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:55:"Read about Chris Trimble‚Äôs teaching in The New Yorker";}i:6115;O:8:"stdClas