Has the economic bedrock of American life turned to quicksand?  Jobs, technology and innovation are vanishing before our eyes.  While China replaces America as the home of the world‚Äôs tallest buildings, biggest cities and fastest trains and computers, we suffer from a pervasive sense of national decline.

As American entrepreneurs and quality workers worry about losing their livelihoods, and college graduates worry about the horizon before them, it is becoming harder to believe that the 21st Century‚Äîalready more than 10 percent over‚Äîwill be a second American Century.

Mark Davis draws on his experience in national politics and knowledge of history to reveal the twin dangers of self-perpetuating pessimism and unfounded optimism.  He examines our current sense of national decline through the lens of history and economic change to define the underlying ‚Äúwicked problems‚Äù of declining standards in health care, education, innovation, and national security and safety. 

After surveying the current electoral scene, Mark Davis sets out four core challenges both parties must rise to meet to reverse America‚Äôs declining fortunes‚Äîand ensure our children will know a better life than we have.";}i:8922;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"202";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:855:"<strong>Richard Torrenzano and Mark Davis--Digital Assassination:</strong> Protecting Your Reputation, Brand, or Business Against Online Attacks

